'''Overall'''
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Category ! width="150"|Balance |- | Retirement |align="center"| $88,500 |- | Emergency Fund |align="center"| $16,000 |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$104,500''' |- |}
=== Year 4 === In Year 4, you now can contribute a total of $32,000 to max out your tax-advantaged space, and you still have another $5,000 to save. With that additional $5,000, you can start to rebuild your emergency fund in the taxable account. So, add $5,000 to your taxable account and allocate it toward the emergency fund. At the same time, you can re-allocate an equal portion in your Roth IRA ($5,000) from being allocated to emergency fund to being allocated to retirement by transferring $5,000 from the money market fund to the stock fund that is allocated for retirement.
At the end of the year, the accounts look like this:
'''Taxable Account''' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"| Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="150"|Note |- | Money Market |align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$1,000 | Emergency Fund | Beginning Balance |- |- | Money Market |align="center"|+ $5,000 | Emergency Fund | Contribution |- | '''Money Market TOTAL''' | align="center"| '''$6,000''' | Emergency Fund | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4" | &nbsp; |- | '''ACCOUNT TOTAL''' |align="center"|'''$6,000''' | Emergency Fund | &nbsp; |- |}
'''Roth IRA'''
''Note that the exchange from the Money Market fund to the Stock fund all happens within the same Roth IRA account.'' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="200"|Note |- | Stocks | align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$10,500 | Retirement | Starting balance |- | Stocks | align="center"| + $7,500 | Retirement | New Annual Contribution |- | Stocks | align="center"| + $5,000 | Retirement | Exch from Money Market |- | '''Stocks Total''' | align="center"| '''$23,000''' | Retirement | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4"|&nbsp; |- | Money Market | align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$15,000 | Emergency Fund | Starting balance |- | Money Market | align="center"| - $5,000 | Emergency Fund | Exch to Stocks/Retirement |- | '''Money Market Total''' | align="center"| '''$10,000''' | Emergency Fund | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4"|&nbsp; |- | '''ACCOUNT TOTAL''' | align="center"| '''$33,000''' | &nbsp; | &nbsp; |- |}
'''401(k)''' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="200"|Note |- | Stocks |align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$78,000 | Retirement | Beginning Balance |- | Stocks |align="center"| + $24,500 | Retirement | Contribution |- | '''Stocks TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$102,500''' | colspan="2" | Retirement |- | colspan="4" | &nbsp; |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$102,500''' | Retirement | &nbsp; |- |}
'''Overall'''
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Category ! width="150"|Balance |- | Retirement |align="center"| $125,000 |- | Emergency Fund |align="center"| $16,000 |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$141,000''' |- |}
=== Year 5 === In Year 5, you can contribute a total of $32,000 to max out your tax-advantaged space, and you have an additional $10,000 to save. Similar to what you did in Year 4, add the $10,000 to your taxable account and allocate it toward your emergency fund. With the addition of $10,000 to your emergency fund in the taxable account, you can exchange the $10,000 in the Roth IRA account that is allocated to the emergency fund, to retirement. You've now built your emergency fund back up in the taxable account.
At the end of this year, your Roth IRA is now allocated 100% to your retirement allocation, and 100% of your emergency fund is back in the taxable account.
At the end of the year, the accounts look like this:
'''Taxable Account''' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"| Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="150"|Note |- | Money Market |align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$6,000 | Emergency Fund | Beginning Balance |- |- | Money Market |align="center"|+ $10,000 | Emergency Fund | Contribution |- | '''Money Market TOTAL''' | align="center"| '''$16,000''' | Emergency Fund | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4" | &nbsp; |- | '''ACCOUNT TOTAL''' |align="center"|'''$16,000''' | Emergency Fund | &nbsp; |- |}
'''Roth IRA'''
''Note that the exchange from the Money Market fund to the Stock fund all happens within the same Roth IRA account.'' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="200"|Note |- | Stocks | align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$23,000 | Retirement | Starting balance |- | Stocks | align="center"| + $7,500 | Retirement | New Annual Contribution |- | Stocks | align="center"| + $10,000 | Retirement | Exch from Money Market |- | '''Stocks Total''' | align="center"| '''$40,500''' | Retirement | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4"|&nbsp; |- | Money Market | align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$10,000 | Emergency fund | Starting balance |- | Money Market | align="center"| - $10,000 | Emergency fund | Exch to Stocks/Retirement |- | '''Money Market Total''' | align="center"| '''$0.00''' | Emergency fund | &nbsp; |- | colspan="4"|&nbsp; |- | '''ACCOUNT TOTAL''' | align="center"| '''$40,500''' | &nbsp; | &nbsp; |- |}
'''401(k)''' {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Fund ! width="150"|Balance ! width="150"|Allocated Toward ! width="200"|Note |- | Stocks |align="center"| &nbsp;&nbsp;$102,500 | Retirement | Beginning Balance |- | Stocks |align="center"| + $24,500 | Retirement | Contribution |- | '''Stocks TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$127,000''' | colspan="2" | Retirement |- | colspan="4" | &nbsp; |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$127,000''' | Retirement | &nbsp; |- |}
'''Overall'''
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Category ! width="150"|Balance |- | Retirement |align="center"| $167,500 |- | Emergency Fund |align="center"| $16,000 |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$183,500''' |- |}
=== Summary of Case Study === If you had left your emergency fund in the taxable account all along, then you wouldn't have been able to get the extra $14,000 of savings in Year 4 and Year 5 into the Roth IRA. Instead, in Year 4 when you have an additional $5,000 to invest, you would only be able to add it to a stock/retirement fund in taxable account, and in Year 5, when you have an additional $10,000 to invest, you would only be able to invest it into the same taxable account.
What both scenarios have in common is that at the end of Year 5, you have $16,000 in the emergency fund in the taxable account, and both scenarios have an identical amount in the 401(k).
But in the Roth as Emergency Fund scenario you have $15,000 more in the Roth IRA. Here is a summary of all '''retirement''' assets in the taxable account and the Roth IRA account at the end of Year 5 when you use the Roth IRA as an emergency fund: {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Account ! width="150"|Balance |- | Taxable |align="center"| $0.00 |- | Roth IRA |align="center"| $40,500 |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$40,500''' |- |} By contrast, here is what your accounts look like if you never availed yourself of the Roth IRA as an emergency fund: {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! width="150"|Account ! width="150"|Balance |- | Taxable |align="center"| $15,000 |- | Roth IRA |align="center"| $25,500 |- | '''TOTAL''' |align="center"| '''$40,500''' |- |}
Clearly, the first option is superior because you have all $40,500 in the Roth IRA.
=== Variations === Variations with this case study: * If the person had to make a withdrawal from the Roth IRA for an emergency, then that would simply deduct that portion from the Roth IRA. Withdrawals for emergencies should start in the taxable account (if there are any emergency funds in the taxable account) first and then move to the Roth IRA. That would, consequently, leave less money to "transfer" from emergency fund to retirement if/when the investor can replenish her emergency fund in a taxable account. * If this person's income and ability to save had not risen as fast, then the remaining $1,000 in the taxable account could have been transferred in Year 4 into the Roth IRA. * This case study began with someone who already has an emergency fund. This case study could also be adapted for someone who is just building an emergency fund. In that case, contributions to the emergency fund could go into the Roth (up to the maximum amount allowed per year).
